#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: sc53
msgctxt "mn15:6.47"
msgid "‘Yo khvāyaṃ puggalo sandiṭṭhiparāmāsī ādhānaggāhī duppaṭinissaggī, ayaṃ me puggalo appiyo amanāpo; "
msgstr "‘This person is attached to their own views, holding them tight and refusing to let go. And I don’t like or approve of this person. "

msgctxt "mn15:6.48"
msgid "ahañceva kho panassaṃ sandiṭṭhiparāmāsī ādhānaggāhī duppaṭinissaggī, ahampāssaṃ paresaṃ appiyo amanāpo’ti. "
msgstr "And if I were to be attached to my own views, holding them tight and refusing to let go, others wouldn’t like or approve of me.’ "

msgctxt "mn15:6.49"
msgid "Evaṃ jānantenāvuso, bhikkhunā ‘asandiṭṭhiparāmāsī bhavissāmi anādhānaggāhī suppaṭinissaggī’ti cittaṃ uppādetabbaṃ. (16) "
msgstr "A mendicant who knows this should give rise to the thought: ‘I will not be attached to my own views, holding them tight, but will let them go easily.’ "

#. HTML: </p><p>
#. REF: nya7, sc54
msgctxt "mn15:7.1"
msgid "Tatrāvuso, bhikkhunā attanāva attānaṃ evaṃ paccavekkhitabbaṃ: "
msgstr "In such a case, a mendicant should check themselves like this: "

msgctxt "mn15:7.2"
msgid "‘kiṃ nu khomhi pāpiccho, pāpikānaṃ icchānaṃ vasaṃ gato’ti? "
msgstr "‘Do I have wicked desires? Have I fallen under the sway of wicked desires?’ "

msgctxt "mn15:7.3"
msgid "Sace, āvuso, bhikkhu paccavekkhamāno evaṃ jānāti: "
msgstr "Suppose that, upon checking, a mendicant knows that "

msgctxt "mn15:7.4"
msgid "‘pāpiccho khomhi, pāpikānaṃ icchānaṃ vasaṃ gato’ti, tenāvuso, bhikkhunā tesaṃyeva pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya vāyamitabbaṃ. "
msgstr "they have fallen under the sway of wicked desires. Then they should make an effort to give up those bad, unskillful qualities. "

msgctxt "mn15:7.5"
msgid "Sace panāvuso, bhikkhu paccavekkhamāno evaṃ jānāti: "
msgstr "But suppose that, upon checking, a mendicant knows that "

msgctxt "mn15:7.6"
msgid "‘na khomhi pāpiccho, na pāpikānaṃ icchānaṃ vasaṃ gato’ti, tenāvuso, bhikkhunā teneva pītipāmojjena vihātabbaṃ ahorattānusikkhinā kusalesu dhammesu. (1) "
msgstr "they haven’t fallen under the sway of wicked desires. Then they should meditate with rapture and joy, training day and night in skillful qualities. … "

